#Scaling X
'''#Scaling X means that we are taking the values of X, and applying an algorithm that scales the larger 
numbers of the different X features to similar sizes. For example, Total Day Charges and Total Customer
Service calls are totally different classes of data, so scale allows us to accurately compare the two properly.
This guarantees that our data won't be warped and inaccurate when we predict our data with ML.
'''

scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(X_train)

X_train = scaler.transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

#The code below creates an Andrews Curve plot
''' This plot is mainly to see if our churn=True data is grouping together.
The curves in the plot don't matter as much as telling if our X features are  clustering to true or false.
The plot below represents Churn=True with Red, and Churn=False with blue.
Based on the plot, we can tell that Churn=True, the Red, isn't clustered very closely with Churn=False. 
We can distincly see the difference between Blue and Red, although some Red values are overlapping with the Blue.
This suggests the two categories have mostly distinct characteristics. 
This is good and will help our ML model.
'''

from pandas.plotting import andrews_curves
#plot size
plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
andrews_curves(dataset2, "Churn", color=["blue", "red"]),
#title
plt.title('Andrews Curves Plot', fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')
#creation of legend
plt.legend(loc=1, prop={'size': 15}, frameon=True,shadow=True, facecolor="white", edgecolor="black")
plt.show()

#Last Data Plot for our Visualization
'''Finally,
The last plot for our most important X features and Y, is to plot a violin plot. 
Violin plots are similar to boxplots, however it represents more of how the data is distributed than the boxplot.
It does this by showing the density of the variable at each value with different shapes. Wider sections
of the violin plot represent a higher probability that members of the population will take on the 
given value; the skinnier sections represent a lower probability.

From the plots below, Red is False for churn, Blue is True. Density is sig. higher for red. 
We can further reaffirm that Churn=True users make more customer service phone calls, have higher 
day charge rates, higher day minutes, and SLIGHTLY higher evening charges. 
We have now confirmed that the features we picked to put in dataset2 is the correct X features.
'''
#creation of subplots, using indices to pick out individual plots
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize =(14, 12))
ax11 = axs[0][0]
ax12 = axs[0][1]
ax21 = axs[1][0]
ax22 = axs[1][1]


sns.set(style="darkgrid")
#creation of violin plots, x and y from dataset 2, separated by Churn true or false
sns.violinplot(ax=ax11, x="Churn", y="Customer service calls", hue="Churn", data=dataset2,
               palette="Pastel1")
sns.violinplot(ax=ax12, x="Churn", y="Total day charge", hue="Churn", data=dataset2,
               palette="Pastel1")
sns.violinplot(ax=ax21, x="Churn", y="Total day minutes", hue="Churn", data=dataset2,
               palette="Pastel1")
sns.violinplot(ax=ax22, x="Churn", y="Total eve charge", hue="Churn", data=dataset,
               palette="Pastel1")

'''KNN Classification
Now it is time to use our ML model. We will use KN Neighbors, which is used for machine learning classification,
which is what this dataset is. We want the model to classify the points as Churn=True or Churn=False

We need to choose a K value, which means that we are picking how many X variables or "neighbors"
to compare the predicted value to. More Neighbors mean smoother grouping, but risk of always placing the 
unknown value in the majority.
A smaller K value might split up the data into different groups too much. However, for this data,
we only have two groups, True or False. So we don't want a huge K value or one that is too small.
Usually, a K value of 1-3 is pretty good. We are going to start with 3 and see which gets us the highest
accuracy. 


'''

# Fitting clasifier to the Training set
# Loading libraries
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, accuracy_score
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

# Instantiate learning model (k = 4
classifier = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=9)

# Fitting the model
classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predicting the Test set results
y_pred = classifier.predict(X_test)

True positive: True Negative: False Positive: False Negative: 
Giving us an idea of how accurate our model is. 
We will use pd.crosstab to format our table telling us which is the true negatives/positives, etc.
'''
print(confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred))

pd.crosstab(y_test, y_pred, rownames=['True'], colnames=['Predicted'], margins=True)

#Recall: model's ability to identify the result
#Precision: model's successful identification - true positive/negative
#accuracy: Overall accuracy of model
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)*100
print('Accuracy of our model is equal ' + str(round(accuracy, 2)) + ' %.')
#our accuracy is good, along with our precision.

Accuracy of our model is equal 100.0 %.
''' Cross Validation Next step is to cross-validate our K value to see what the optimal K value should be. We are going to do this by applying cross_val_score to a range of numbers in a list from 1 to 50, as values for K. ''' k_list = list(range(1,50,2)) # creating list of cv scores cv_scores = [] for k in k_list: knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k) scores = cross_val_score(knn, X_train, y_train, cv=10, scoring='accuracy') #take the mean of the scores and append to cv_scores list. cv_scores.append(scores.mean())
In [403]:
# changing to misclassification error
#this uses list comprehension to create a list for 1 - all values in cv_scores, for misclassification error
MSE = [1 - x for x in cv_scores]

plt.figure()
plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
plt.title('The optimal number of neighbors', fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Number of Neighbors K', fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Misclassification Error', fontsize=15)
sns.set_style("whitegrid")
plt.plot(k_list, MSE)

plt.show()

# finding best k
#This test presents the optimal number below by using misclassification
#error from the list we made above
best_k = k_list[MSE.index(min(MSE))]
print("The optimal number of neighbors is %d." % best_k)

The optimal number of neighbors is 9.

#First, One more Cross Validation for K neighbors below:
'''
GridSearchCV is cross validation that puts various values
for K in our model, with multiple layers of cross validation.
For example, is cv=5, we are conducting a 5-fold cross validation,
using 5 sets of data. 1-4 as training, and 5 as testing. 
'''
#import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

#gridSearch takes neighbors in range from 1 to 50 to test model
param_grid = {'n_neighbors':np.arange(1,50)}
#neighborsclassifier
knn = KNeighborsClassifier()
#5 cross validation test cv-5
knn_cv= GridSearchCV(knn,param_grid,cv=5)
knn_cv.fit(X,y)
